Part 3: Working with Categorical Variables¶

The columns cut, color, and clarity are categorical variables whose values represent discrete categories into which the diamonds can be classified. In this part, I will create lists specifying the order for each of the three categorical variables.

In [9]:
cut_levels = ['Fair', 'Good', 'Very Good', 'Premium', 'Ideal']
color_levels = ['J', 'I', 'H', 'G', 'F', 'E', 'D']
clarity_levels = ['I1', 'SI2', 'SI1', 'VS2', 'VS1', 'VVS2', 'VVS1', 'IF']

Use the lists to set the correct order for the three categorical variables.

In [10]:
diamonds.cut = pd.Categorical(diamonds.cut, cut_levels)
diamonds.color = pd.Categorical(diamonds.color, color_levels)
diamonds.clarity = pd.Categorical(diamonds.clarity, clarity_levels)

Following are lists of named colors to serve as palettes for later visualizations.

In [11]:
cut_pal = ['red', 'orange', 'yellow', 'green', 'blue']
color_pal = ['brown', 'purple', 'blue', 'green', 'olive', 'yellow', 'orange']
clarity_pal = ["dodgerblue", "forestgreen", "gold", "firebrick", "darkorchid", "deeppink", "tomato", "cyan"]

Part 5: Scatterplots of Price Against Carat¶

In this part, I will explore the relationship between the price and carat attributes by generating scatter plots.

In [15]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8,6])
plt.scatter(x=diamonds.carat,
            y=diamonds.price,
            s=20,
            alpha=0.4,
            c='darkcyan')
plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Price (in $)')
plt.title('Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size')
plt.show()

Following will be the same plot as above, but I will color the points according to their clarity.

In [16]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8,6])
for level, color in zip(clarity_levels, clarity_pal):
    plt.scatter(x=diamonds[diamonds.clarity==level].carat,
                y=diamonds[diamonds.clarity==level].price,
                s=20,
                alpha=0.4,
                c=color,
                label=level)
plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Price (in $)')
plt.title('Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Next, I will separate the points for each of the eight clarity levels into its own subplot.

In [17]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=4, figsize=[12,6])
for level, ax, color in zip(clarity_levels, axs.flat, clarity_pal):
    ax.scatter(x=diamonds[diamonds.clarity==level].carat,
               y=diamonds[diamonds.clarity==level].price,
               s=20,
               alpha=0.4,
               c=color)
    ax.set_xlabel('Carat Size')
    ax.set_ylabel('Price (in $)')
    ax.set_title(level)
    ax.set_xlim([0,4])
    ax.set_ylim([0,20000])
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Part 6: Applying Logarithmic Transformations¶

In this part, I will apply logarithmic transformations to the price and carat columns and explore the distribution of these transformed variables.

Add two new columns to the diamonds dataset to store the transformed variables.

In [18]:
diamonds['ln_carat'] = np.log(diamonds.carat)
diamonds['ln_price'] = np.log(diamonds.price)

Use histograms to display the distribution of the diamond prices as well as the log of the diamond prices.

In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12, 4])

plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.hist(diamonds.price,
            bins=20,
            edgecolor='black',
            color='thistle')
plt.xlabel('Price')
plt.title('Histogram of Prices')

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.hist(diamonds.ln_price,
            bins=20,
            edgecolor='black',
            color='indigo')
plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Price')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Log-Prices')

plt.show()

Use histograms to display the distribution of the carat sizes and the log of the carat sizes.

In [20]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12, 4])

plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.hist(diamonds.carat,
            bins=20,
            edgecolor='black',
            color='springgreen')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Carat Sizes')

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.hist(diamonds.ln_carat,
            bins=20,
            edgecolor='black',
            color='forestgreen')
plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Log-Carat Sizes')

plt.show()

Part 7: Scatterplot of Transformed Variables¶

In this part, I will recreate the second scatterplot from Part 5 with the transformed variables instead of the original values.

I will create a scatterplot of ln_price against ln_carat with points colored according to their clarity.

In [21]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8,6])
for level, color in zip(clarity_levels, clarity_pal):
    plt.scatter(x=diamonds[diamonds.clarity==level].ln_carat,
                y=diamonds[diamonds.clarity==level].ln_price,
                s=20,
                alpha=0.4,
                c=color,
                label=level)
plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Natural Log of Price')
plt.title('Relationship between Log-Price and Log-Carat Size')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
